WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.320
 So now what we're going to do is we're going to talk about how we can represent links in a database.

00:00:05.320 --> 00:00:09.720
 And so up till now I've just been drawing arrows and just assuming that you know how to do them.

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:10.880
 And so here's some arrows, right?

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:16.000
 We got some book instance rows that can somehow magically connect to some book rows,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.720
 and some book rows that can magically connect to a language row.

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:23.000
 And so there's a way that we do this.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.440
 And we put what we call a key column in every one of our tables.

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:34.720
 Key column, we call this the primary key, and we often call the name of the column the ID.

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:38.160
 There's a way in the database to make it what's called auto-increment and

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:41.240
 primary key and index it so it's really fast.

00:00:41.240 --> 00:00:43.960
 And so that then becomes the handle.

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:48.400
 The primary keys are like the destination endpoint of the arrows, right?

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:54.680
 So that's how we say English becomes language number one.

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:59.320
 And Wisdom of Crowds is book number one, and Introduction to Networking is book

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:00.560
 number two.

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:05.520
 And so the ID is something that we then can use throughout the rest of the system.

00:01:05.520 --> 00:01:09.680
 Integer replication is not a problem, okay?

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:14.840
 And so then what we do is we put columns in that we call foreign keys, right?

00:01:14.840 --> 00:01:18.480
 And so those foreign keys are the starting point of the arrows, right?

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:20.000
 So book_id.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.320
 Now by convention, we name these by the name of the table followed by an underscore

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:27.040
 followed by the word ID.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:31.600
 These are called foreign keys, foreign keys.

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:36.080
 And so by having a foreign key everywhere we need to start an arrow and

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:38.880
 a primary key everywhere we need to end an arrow.

00:01:38.880 --> 00:01:41.600
 Now really we pretty much put primary keys on every table so

00:01:41.600 --> 00:01:44.520
 that every row of every table has a primary key.

00:01:44.520 --> 00:01:47.680
 Now in this example, I've just got one foreign key per table, but

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:49.520
 you can have more than one foreign key per table.

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:53.040
 There could be another column here that points off to another table.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:53.760
 But that's it.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:54.680
 That's how we do it.

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:59.840
 We just simply add these integer numbers and then we kind of maintain them and

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:01.000
 put them all together.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:08.200
 So like I said, the primary key is that column that we add and

00:02:08.200 --> 00:02:10.320
 that is our handle for the rows.

00:02:10.320 --> 00:02:13.320
 And then the foreign key is the column that we add to a table so

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:14.840
 that we can point to something.

00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:20.040
 So basically once we create these foreign key columns and

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:24.960
 the primary key columns, we start being able to build using these links.

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:27.800
 We can build the links that replicate the data model

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:30.000
 that ends up being our picture, okay?

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:31.800
 And so that's how they work.

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:36.040
 Up next, we're gonna talk about how we represent these links in Django.

00:02:36.040 --> 00:02:46.040
 [MUSIC]

